---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { media } from '../media.js';

// References preserved from the prior site (titles and source links only;
// the source did not list authors/year/journal, so none are invented here).
const references = [
  {
    title: 'An agile design-to-simulation workflow using a new conforming moving least squares method',
    url: 'https://www.osti.gov/biblio/1569655/',
  },
  {
    title: 'Conforming window functions for meshfree methods',
    url: 'https://www.osti.gov/pages/biblio/1492348',
  },
  {
    title: 'Treatment of near-incompressibility in meshfree and immersed-particle methods',
    url: 'https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s40571-019-00238-z',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="Aperi-Mech"
  description="Aperi-Mech is a solid mechanics solver built on the Conforming Reproducing Kernel method and designed to be driven by AI agents."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">Solver</p>
      <h1>Aperi-Mech</h1>
      <p class="hero__lede">
        Aperi-Mech is our flagship solver, designed to run efficiently with an AI
        agent. It includes an internal mesher designed for AI, so an agent can
        generate meshes efficiently without wasting tokens.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap overview">
      <div class="overview__head">
        <p class="eyebrow">Capabilities</p>
        <h2>What it does</h2>
      </div>
      <ul class="points">
        <li>
          Supports unstructured meshes. Generate analysis-ready meshes from
          imperfect geometry or raw scans without manual cleanup.
        </li>
        <li>
          Explicit transient dynamics, implicit dynamics, and statics. All done
          with matrix-free solvers, no global assembly required.
        </li>
        <li>
          Performance portable: single codebase runs natively on CPUs and GPUs
          with no vendor lock-in.
        </li>
        <li>
          Meshfree and finite element methods in a single framework.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap overview">
      <div class="overview__head">
        <p class="eyebrow">Method</p>
        <h2>Conforming Reproducing Kernel</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The Conforming Reproducing Kernel Method (CRK) is the result of extensive
          research focusing on the application of mesh-free methods to expedite
          simulation development. In most simulation processes, a significant
          bottleneck lies in the effort required to generate a suitable
          discretization, known as &ldquo;meshing,&rdquo; from the given geometry.
          This task is particularly critical for dynamic structural analyses, as
          computational costs are directly linked to mesh quality.
        </p>
        <p>
          CRK offers an effective solution for simulating scenarios involving
          complex geometries, low-quality meshes, and nearly incompressible
          materials, all without increasing the computational cost to obtain
          accurate solutions.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap overview">
      <div class="overview__head">
        <p class="eyebrow">Examples</p>
        <h2>Worked examples</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="overview__body">
        <figure class="example">
          <video
            class="example__video"
            poster={media('/front_out_poster.jpg')}
            playsinline
            controls
            preload="metadata"
            aria-label="Landslide simulation animation"
          >
            <source src={media('/front_out.mp4')} type="video/mp4" />
            Your browser does not support the video tag.
          </video>
          <figcaption class="example__caption">
            This landslide simulation uses real terrain data from a lidar scan.
            No manual geometry cleanup was involved. The
            simulation uses explicit dynamics with a Drucker-Prager material model
            for the muddy soil in the middle of the hill. The topographic dataset
            came from the Geometrics Lab at Oregon State University, using a ground
            filter developed by EZDataMD to strip out vegetation, structures, and
            other noise.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="example example--spaced">
          <img
            class="example__img"
            src={media('/lunar_landslide.png')}
            alt="Time series of a simulated landslide on the slope of the Moon's Tycho crater, at initial time, 80, 120, and 160 seconds"
            width="1224"
            height="476"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption class="example__caption">
            A simulation of a landslide on the Tycho crater, performed with
            Aperi-Mech on an STL pulled from
            <a href="https://science.nasa.gov/3d-resources/moon-tycho/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NASA's 3D resources</a>.
            Performance testing was done on an NVIDIA H100 GPU and AMD EPYC 7V12
            processors. For reference, on this problem a single H100 GPU ran the
            simulation about as fast as 32 CPU cores.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap overview">
      <div class="overview__head">
        <p class="eyebrow">References</p>
        <h2>Published work</h2>
      </div>
      <ol class="reflist">
        {references.map((ref) => (
          <li>
            <a href={ref.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">{ref.title}</a>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
